</comment>
                            <comment id="12844858" author="adeneche" created="Sat, 13 Mar 2010 11:09:15 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;just committed the patch. Should work (hopefully).&lt;br/&gt;
Work is still in progress, the next patch should allow the user to actually store the predictions in a text file&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12844928" author="adeneche" created="Sat, 13 Mar 2010 17:41:22 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;updated &lt;a href=&quot;http://cwiki.apache.org/MAHOUT/partial-implementation.html&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;Wiki page&lt;/a&gt; to explain how to build a decision forest on the NSL-KDD dataset and how to classify new data&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12850480" author="adeneche" created="Sat, 27 Mar 2010 06:39:16 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;committed the ability to classify a directory of files and updated the &lt;a href=&quot;http://cwiki.apache.org/confluence/display/MAHOUT/Partial+Implementation&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;Wiki page&lt;/a&gt; accordingly.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12853185" author="adeneche" created="Sat, 3 Apr 2010 20:12:47 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;committed a basic mapreduce version of TestForest. If you pass &quot;-mr&quot; to TestForest it will use Hadoop to classify the data. Each input file is processed by exactly one mapper. For now, you &lt;b&gt;cannot&lt;/b&gt; compute the confusion matrix with the mapreduce version...this should come in a the next commit&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12911170" author="adeneche" created="Sun, 19 Sep 2010 07:41:35 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;This should be the final patch for this issue. Allowing the mapreduce classification to compute the confusion matrix&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12911171" author="tdunning" created="Sun, 19 Sep 2010 07:52:25 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;Ok.  Committed the patch. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Back to you Deneche.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
